BUSINESS RULES (CORE)
1) Order Types
- SALES: catch-all for small parts orders.
- PROJECT: catch-all for system-level orders (longer-lived).

2) SALES BaseToken Year Rule (CONFIG-DRIVEN)
- BaseToken series is NOT based on DateReceived.
- 576000–576999 used during calendar year 2026.
- On 1/1/2027 BaseToken series rolls to 577000 regardless of current 576NNN progress.
- If 576999 is reached before 12/31/2026, handle exception if/when it occurs.
- Cutover: current paper log is ~576092; sequencing in Dataverse was intentionally seeded at 576100; will be set to “last used + 1” at go-live.

3) OrderNumber Format
<OrderBaseToken>-<QualifierCode><SystemLetter><Seq3>-<BackorderNo2>
Example: 576040-YBP001-00
- QualifierCode is TWO letters (e.g., YB = Yellow/Blue); about 6 qualifiers.
- SystemLetter is ONE letter (e.g., P = Product); similar count.
- Seq3 is always 001–999.
- BackorderNo starts at 00; Create Backorder increments it later.

4) One Order per Qualifier-Row
- Each “qualifier row” generates one SalesOrder record.
- Example batch: 576040-YB P001-00, 576040-YB P002-00 … 576040-YB P00N-00 (conceptually).

DATAVERSE TABLES CREATED (POC FOUNDATION)
A) AppConfig
- Columns: ConfigKey (primary name), ConfigValue, Description.
- Alternate key active on ConfigKey.
- Uses built-in Modified On/By (do not create LastUpdated/UpdatedBy custom fields).
- Data rows include: CurrentSalesYear=2026 plus other seed parameters (if used).

Logical names confirmed from Dataverse output:
- hmcsales_configkey
- hmcsales_configvalue
- hmcsales_description

B) SalesBaseTokenSeq
- Purpose: concurrency-safe SALES BaseToken allocator.
- Columns: SalesYearName (text primary name), SalesYear (whole number), Seed (whole number), NextToken (whole number).
- Alternate key active on SalesYear.
- Seed/NextToken set to 576100 intentionally for 2026 to match cutover state.

Logical names confirmed:
- hmcsales_salesyear (whole number)
- hmcsales_seed
- hmcsales_nexttoken
- hmcsales_salesbasetokenseqid (row id GUID)

C) OrderSeq
- Purpose: concurrency-safe 001–999 sequence per domain.
- Domain key (alternate key): (Scope, BaseToken, QualifierCode, SystemLetter).
- Columns include: Scope (text), BaseToken (text), QualifierCode (text), SystemLetter (text), NextSeq (whole number), plus OrderSeqName (text label).
- Important: Dataverse primary name formatting is not configurable; OrderSeqName is set in Flow.

Logical names (schema names as recorded in Maker):
- hmcsales_Scope
- hmcsales_BaseToken
- hmcsales_QualifierCode
- hmcsales_SystemLetter
- hmcsales_NextSeq
(Note: for Power Automate OData filters, logical names may need lowercase (hmcsales_scope etc.) depending on connector behavior.)

POWER AUTOMATE POC FLOW (SEQUENCING HARNESS)
Flow: POC_AllocateOrderNumber (manual trigger)
- Inputs (manual trigger): Scope, QualifierCode, SystemLetter
- Lessons learned:
  1) Variables must be initialized ONCE at top level. Use Set variable inside branches/loops.
  2) Dataverse Filter rows requires OData string filters using logical/schema names, not display names.
  3) Copilot rewrote $filter into boolean and(...) expressions; that breaks List rows ($filter becomes false). Use concat(...) to build OData filter string.

Working behavior:
1) Read AppConfig row for CurrentSalesYear using filter:
   hmcsales_configkey eq 'CurrentSalesYear'
2) Allocate BaseToken:
   - List rows SalesBaseTokenSeq filter: hmcsales_salesyear eq varSalesYear
   - FALSE branch (row exists): set varBaseToken = hmcsales_nexttoken; update hmcsales_nexttoken = varBaseToken + 1
3) Allocate OrderSeq:
   - List rows OrderSeq by domain (Scope/BaseToken/QualifierCode/SystemLetter) using OData filter string (concat).
   - If missing: set varSeq=1; create OrderSeq row with NextSeq=2; OrderSeqName = Scope-BaseToken-QualifierCode-SystemLetter
   - If exists: set varSeq = existing NextSeq; update NextSeq = varSeq + 1
4) Compose OrderNumber:
   <BaseToken>-<QualifierCode><SystemLetter><Seq3>-00
Example compose observed: "576106-YBP001-00"

